\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab - Why can nothing have energy? }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab -the quantum vacuum is a complicated state. It is not \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91empty\u8217\'92. Vacuum fluctuations.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \tab -QFT says vacuum fluctuations with no shortest wavelength. So this makes calculations of vacuum specious - infinity. We think this is a limitation of the range of validity of QFT? At very short wavelengths, something must happen to cut off short wavelengths at infinity. A candidate is the effects of quantum gravity, which we don\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t understand. So they cut off these wavelengths at the planck scale, scale of quantum gravity. Using this cutoff, the estimated vacuum energy density is too large. By 120 orders of magnitude!}
